-v">url</span><span class="crayon-o">-</span><span class="crayon-v">pattern</span><span class="crayon-o">&gt;</span><span class="crayon-o">/</span><span class="crayon-o">*</span><span class="crayon-o">&lt;</span><span class="crayon-o">/</span><span class="crayon-v">url</span><span class="crayon-o">-</span><span class="crayon-v">pattern</span><span class="crayon-o">&gt;</span></div>\r\n<div id="crayon-5909fd0acab5e879881687-21" class="crayon-line"><span class="crayon-h">    </span><span class="crayon-o">&lt;</span><span class="crayon-o">/</span><span class="crayon-v">servlet</span><span class="crayon-o">-</span><span class="crayon-v">mapping</span><span class="crayon-o">&gt;</span></div>\r\n<div id="crayon-5909fd0acab5e879881687-22" class="crayon-line crayon-striped-line"><span class="crayon-o">&lt;</span><span class="crayon-o">/</span><span class="crayon-v">web</span><span class="crayon-o">-</span><span class="crayon-v">app</span><span class="crayon-o">&gt;</span></div>\r\n<div id="crayon-5909fd0acab5e879881687-23" class="crayon-line"></div>\r\n</div></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\nReplace the placeholders with your own values, and then run <code>gradle appRun</code>. If everything builds correctly, let’s fire up <a href="https://www.getpostman.com/">Postman</a> and make a POST request, like this:\r\n\r\n<img src="https://www.nexmo.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/postman-request.png" alt="Making a request with Postman" />\r\n\r\nI hope it worked! So now you’ve built a REST Web service for sending SMS messages! In reality, there’s lots more things you’d want to do before deploying this, like adding authentication (otherwise anyone could send a message using your Nexmo account!), a nice Web form for posting to the service, and improving the error handling – but this is a good start!\r\n\r\nSo far we’ve learned how to send SMS messages with Java. In the next post, we’ll extend this service to receive SMS messages sent to your Nexmo number.\r\n<h2>References</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://docs.nexmo.com/messaging/sms-api/api-reference">Nexmo SMS API Reference</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://github.com/nexmo/nexmo-java">Nexmo Client Library for Java</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCategorised in: <a href="https://www.nexmo.com/blog/category/developers-2/" rel="tag">Developers</a>, <a href="https://www.nexmo.com/blog/category/messaging/" rel="tag">Messaging</a>, <a href="https://www.nexmo.com/blog/category/sms/" rel="tag">SMS</a>, <a href="https://www.nexmo.com/blog/category/developers-2/tutorial/" rel="tag">Tutorial</a>\r\n\r\nThis post was written by <a title="Posts by Mark Smith" href="https://www.nexmo.com/blog/author/judy2k/" rel="author">Mark Smith</a>', 'How to Send SMS Messages With Java and Nexmo', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '124-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-03 15:56:06', '2017-05-03 15:56:06', '', 124, 'http://localhost:8080/Nexmo/Source/BE/124-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
